04468nam a22006855i 9781400821822DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19951995nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008218227 a10.1515/97814008218222doi  a(DE-B1597)446133  a(OCoLC)979577719  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS777.75.W54 1995 7aHIS0080002bisacsh00aWild Lily, Prairie Fire :bChina's Road to Democracy, Yan'an to Tian'anmen, 1942-1989 /ced. by Alan Hunter, Gregor Benton.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[1995] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tA NOTE ON PRONUNCIATION -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER ONE. WILD LILY, 1942 -- tCHAPTER TWO. THE HUNDRED FLOWERS, 1957 -- tCHAPTER THREE. CULTURAL REVOLUTION, 1966–1976 -- tCHAPTER FOUR. CHINA SPRING, 1979–1981 -- tCHAPTER FIVE. PRAIRIE FIRE, 1989 -- tCHAPTER SIX. THE INTELLECTUALS’ CRITIQUE -- tAPPENDIX: SOURCES OF THE TEXTS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGregor Benton and Alan Hunter provide here a source book of documents of democratic dissent under Chinese Communism, most of them previously untranslated and difficult to find in the West. Ranging from eye-witness accounts of a massacre to theoretical critiques of Chinese Marxist thought, these essays are among the most powerful and important works of Chinese dissident literature written in this century. An extensive introduction maintains that the documents reveal a tradition of democratic thought and practice that traces its descent to the New Culture Movement of the 1910s and the founding generation of the Chinese Communist Party. Far from being a late twentieth-century import (along with capitalist economics) from Europe, Japan, and the United States, this tradition of dissent is deeply embedded in the experience of China's revolutionary movements.The story of Chinese Communism has often been reduced to uniformity not only by political bureaucrats in China but by Western scholarship derived from official Chinese histories. Wild Lily, Prairie Fire paints a far richer picture. The book calls into question many of the usual beliefs about the relation between democracy and communism, at least in the Chinese case, which may now be seen to depart from the Soviet model in yet another crucial respect.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aBenton, Gregor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBinyan, Liu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Alan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082182240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400821822423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400821822.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK